00:13:40.736 --> 00:13:42.466 A:middle
So, the central class
you're going

00:13:42.466 --> 00:13:44.716 A:middle
to be using a lot is
called GCController.

00:13:45.046 --> 00:13:47.016 A:middle
You're going to be using this
to connect to controllers

00:13:47.666 --> 00:13:51.636 A:middle
and instances of this class
represent a connected controller

00:13:51.636 --> 00:13:52.356 A:middle
to your device.

00:13:53.336 --> 00:13:54.716 A:middle
Now, this is the same class

00:13:55.046 --> 00:13:57.826 A:middle
for all three supported
controller types.

WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:14:00.816 --> 00:14:03.066 A:middle
GCController has a
lot of capabilities.

00:14:03.746 --> 00:14:05.566 A:middle
It allows you to
find controllers.

00:14:06.166 --> 00:14:07.876 A:middle
So, we have methods
so that you can query

00:14:07.876 --> 00:14:10.376 A:middle
which controllers are currently
connected to my device.

00:14:11.466 --> 00:14:13.126 A:middle
Sometimes you might
want to be notified

00:14:13.276 --> 00:14:15.736 A:middle
as controllers are
connected and disconnected

00:14:15.786 --> 00:14:17.746 A:middle
and we have ways for
you to know that.

00:14:18.476 --> 00:14:22.666 A:middle
And there's also ways for you
to discover wireless controllers

00:14:22.666 --> 00:14:24.516 A:middle
that haven't been used
with this device before.

00:14:28.616 --> 00:14:30.836 A:middle
GCController also
provides you ways

00:14:30.836 --> 00:14:33.776 A:middle
to read the inputs
off of the device.

00:14:34.106 --> 00:14:36.696 A:middle
So, again, how you know where
the D-pad is being pressed,

00:14:37.016 --> 00:14:39.776 A:middle
thumbsticks, triggers and so on.

00:14:41.276 --> 00:14:43.306 A:middle
And lastly, it gives
you information

00:14:43.306 --> 00:14:45.166 A:middle
about the controller whether

00:14:45.166 --> 00:14:46.856 A:middle
or not it's a form-fitting
controller.

00:14:47.916 --> 00:14:50.946 A:middle
The vendor who manufactured
this controller perhaps to show

00:14:50.946 --> 00:14:54.306 A:middle
in a player facing UI like
in a team picker dialogue.

00:14:54.976 --> 00:15:00.076 A:middle
And also gives you the player
index which is surfaced

WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:15:00.286 --> 00:15:03.906 A:middle
in the physical controller
via the player indicator LEDs.

00:15:03.906 --> 00:15:08.936 A:middle
So, let's talk about
connecting and disconnecting.

00:15:10.406 --> 00:15:13.516 A:middle
We have a class method called
controllers on GCController

00:15:14.066 --> 00:15:15.646 A:middle
and this gives you an array

00:15:15.646 --> 00:15:17.416 A:middle
of the currently
connected controllers.

00:15:18.386 --> 00:15:21.456 A:middle
The array instances or the
array elements are instances

00:15:21.456 --> 00:15:22.896 A:middle
of type GCController.

00:15:24.046 --> 00:15:26.906 A:middle
And if there are no currently
connected controllers then this

00:15:26.906 --> 00:15:28.066 A:middle
array will return empty.

00:15:28.686 --> 00:15:33.466 A:middle
Now, the beauty of this is that
controllers as they're connected

00:15:33.466 --> 00:15:36.976 A:middle
and disconnected this
method automatically update

00:15:37.036 --> 00:15:37.966 A:middle
that information for you.

00:15:38.576 --> 00:15:39.956 A:middle
So, you can be guaranteed

00:15:40.346 --> 00:15:43.706 A:middle
that whenever you call this
method you have a current idea

00:15:43.706 --> 00:15:45.316 A:middle
of which controllers
are connected.

00:15:45.556 --> 00:15:49.476 A:middle
Let's look at a code example.

00:15:49.886 --> 00:15:51.626 A:middle
A lot of games will choose

00:15:51.626 --> 00:15:55.406 A:middle
to have a central method that's
called throughout their game

00:15:55.696 --> 00:15:57.976 A:middle
and it resolves new
controllers that come in.

00:15:58.146 --> 00:15:59.966 A:middle
And in this example
we're calling

00:15:59.966 --> 00:16:01.736 A:middle
that method set up controllers.

WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:16:02.606 --> 00:16:04.186 A:middle
The first thing we
do at the top of set

00:16:04.186 --> 00:16:06.996 A:middle
up controllers is we call
the controllers class method.

00:16:07.036 --> 00:16:09.506 A:middle
And we take all the currently
connected controllers

00:16:09.506 --> 00:16:12.146 A:middle
and we cache them into our
controller array property.

00:16:13.696 --> 00:16:17.496 A:middle
Then based on whether or not
we have controllers we can

00:16:17.496 --> 00:16:18.006 A:middle
take action.

00:16:19.136 --> 00:16:21.406 A:middle
Keep this method in
mind set up controllers.

00:16:21.456 --> 00:16:28.676 A:middle
I'm going to be referring to it
throughout the rest of the talk.

00:16:28.846 --> 00:16:30.426 A:middle
Sometimes you don't want to be--

00:16:31.026 --> 00:16:32.016 A:middle
sometimes you don't want

00:16:32.016 --> 00:16:34.586 A:middle
to necessarily ask what
controllers are currently

00:16:34.586 --> 00:16:37.086 A:middle
connected right now rather
you want to be notified

00:16:37.086 --> 00:16:39.296 A:middle
when a controller
connects and disconnects.

00:16:40.066 --> 00:16:42.836 A:middle
And we provide capabilities for
you to get notified of that.

00:16:43.536 --> 00:16:46.756 A:middle
Using NSNotificationCenter
you can add observers

00:16:47.606 --> 00:16:50.576 A:middle
when called GCController
did connect notification.

00:16:51.106 --> 00:16:54.106 A:middle
This is for obviously detecting
when controllers connect.

00:16:54.916 --> 00:16:57.476 A:middle
Similarly, to be notified

00:16:57.476 --> 00:17:01.066 A:middle
when a controller disconnects
we have GCController did

WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:17:01.066 --> 00:17:02.446 A:middle
disconnect notification.

00:17:03.876 --> 00:17:05.185 A:middle
You'll notice in this example,

00:17:05.846 --> 00:17:08.776 A:middle
the selector we've chosen is
our set up controller's method

00:17:09.016 --> 00:17:10.386 A:middle
that you saw on the
previous screen.

00:17:10.866 --> 00:17:13.776 A:middle
So, as controllers are connected
and disconnected we're going

00:17:13.776 --> 00:17:15.606 A:middle
to be funneling back
into that method.

00:17:16.175 --> 00:17:24.636 A:middle
Now, some controllers are going
to be wireless and these types

00:17:24.636 --> 00:17:26.646 A:middle
of controllers need
to be discovered

00:17:26.726 --> 00:17:29.416 A:middle
and paired before the
first time they're used

00:17:29.416 --> 00:17:30.616 A:middle
with a particular device.

00:17:32.156 --> 00:17:34.366 A:middle
These generally only
needs to happen once.

00:17:34.926 --> 00:17:38.246 A:middle
Once the user has paired
a wireless controller

00:17:38.316 --> 00:17:41.816 A:middle
with the device then after
that the controller will

00:17:41.816 --> 00:17:43.996 A:middle
automatically be recognized
and we don't need to go

00:17:44.066 --> 00:17:46.486 A:middle
through this discovery
paring process again.

00:17:48.266 --> 00:17:51.536 A:middle
So, as game developers you
can afford a convenience

00:17:51.536 --> 00:17:53.346 A:middle
to your players and allow them

00:17:53.346 --> 00:17:54.746 A:middle
to do this rate within
your game.

00:17:55.376 --> 00:17:57.026 A:middle
This is great for players

00:17:57.026 --> 00:17:59.656 A:middle
who have just unboxed their
brand new controller and go

00:17:59.656 --> 00:18:01.966 A:middle
to your game first
and don't have to--

WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:18:01.966 --> 00:18:04.646 A:middle
or rather they can
jump into the game

00:18:04.646 --> 00:18:05.826 A:middle
without having to
leave your game.

00:18:06.426 --> 00:18:10.346 A:middle
So, you can just initiate
this discovery process

00:18:10.516 --> 00:18:13.526 A:middle
with the method that we call
start wireless controller

00:18:13.526 --> 00:18:15.256 A:middle
discovery with completion
handler.

00:18:16.166 --> 00:18:19.026 A:middle
When you call this
wireless discovery kicks off

00:18:19.026 --> 00:18:21.906 A:middle
asynchronously and it doesn't
block you're able to go

00:18:21.906 --> 00:18:24.966 A:middle
about your business and your
app can remain responsive.

00:18:25.506 --> 00:18:29.706 A:middle
And whenever the discovery
process finishes your supplied

00:18:29.706 --> 00:18:31.016 A:middle
completion handler is called.

00:18:31.056 --> 00:18:34.506 A:middle
And it's called in one
of three situations.

00:18:34.676 --> 00:18:37.756 A:middle
One, either all the controllers
have been discovered.

00:18:39.206 --> 00:18:44.646 A:middle
Two, the discovery process
has timed-out or three,

00:18:44.646 --> 00:18:48.436 A:middle
you've explicitly told it to
stop early, and if you decide

00:18:48.436 --> 00:18:51.656 A:middle
to do that you can do so via
the stop wireless controller

00:18:51.656 --> 00:18:52.496 A:middle
discovery method.

00:18:53.006 --> 00:18:55.956 A:middle
Now, you're going
to want to use this

00:18:55.956 --> 00:18:57.816 A:middle
in conjunction with
notifications.

00:18:58.336 --> 00:19:03.276 A:middle
So, as you kickoff the wireless
discovery process the discovery

WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:19:03.276 --> 00:19:05.296 A:middle
is happening asynchronously
in the background

00:19:05.646 --> 00:19:08.706 A:middle
and while that's happening and
controllers are being discovered

00:19:08.706 --> 00:19:11.146 A:middle
and paired notifications fire.

00:19:11.246 --> 00:19:13.396 A:middle
And so, if you set up the
notifications that I showed you

00:19:13.396 --> 00:19:16.166 A:middle
on the previous slide that
will be happened automatically.

00:19:16.166 --> 00:19:17.996 A:middle
So, you can see we're
building this in layers.

00:19:17.996 --> 00:19:23.006 A:middle
Let's look at a code example.

00:19:24.036 --> 00:19:26.316 A:middle
In this example, we've
arbitrarily chosen

00:19:26.316 --> 00:19:29.836 A:middle
that the user-- we're going
to allow the user the ability

00:19:29.866 --> 00:19:31.936 A:middle
to start the wireless
discovery themselves.

00:19:32.516 --> 00:19:33.656 A:middle
So, maybe the user hits a button

00:19:33.656 --> 00:19:36.806 A:middle
in your interface say the
first thing we do is start

00:19:36.806 --> 00:19:38.626 A:middle
up a spinner so that
the user knows

00:19:38.626 --> 00:19:40.616 A:middle
that they're input
action has been accepted

00:19:40.616 --> 00:19:43.326 A:middle
and we kickoff the start
wireless controller discovery

00:19:43.326 --> 00:19:44.676 A:middle
with completion handler method.

00:19:45.596 --> 00:19:47.436 A:middle
Now, again, this
happens asynchronously,

00:19:47.776 --> 00:19:50.556 A:middle
and whenever it returns
we can take action

00:19:50.556 --> 00:19:51.446 A:middle
and the first thing we're doing

00:19:51.446 --> 00:19:53.076 A:middle
in this case is we're
stopping our spinner.

00:19:54.046 --> 00:19:56.296 A:middle
Since we're affording
the users the ability

00:19:56.296 --> 00:19:59.346 A:middle
to start this process themselves
we should also provide them a

00:19:59.346 --> 00:20:00.906 A:middle
way to cancel it.

WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:20:02.256 --> 00:20:04.826 A:middle
And you do that again
by calling stop wireless

00:20:04.826 --> 00:20:05.726 A:middle
controller discovery.

00:20:06.876 --> 00:20:09.276 A:middle
You'll note that this method
doesn't take a completion

00:20:09.276 --> 00:20:12.686 A:middle
handler because when this is
called the completion handler

00:20:12.686 --> 00:20:15.016 A:middle
in the start method
above is called for you.

00:20:15.926 --> 00:20:18.746 A:middle
And it's safe to call stop
wireless controller discovery

00:20:18.746 --> 00:20:21.706 A:middle
even if your start wireless
controller discovery handler has

00:20:21.706 --> 00:20:22.236 A:middle
already called.

00:20:26.656 --> 00:20:28.786 A:middle
Now, I have a few
caveats to mention

00:20:28.786 --> 00:20:31.146 A:middle
to you regarding
connecting and disconnecting.

00:20:33.266 --> 00:20:37.446 A:middle
Controllers take time to be
recognized on app start up.

00:20:38.316 --> 00:20:39.566 A:middle
Now, the framework does this

00:20:39.646 --> 00:20:41.806 A:middle
for you asynchronously
and automatically.

00:20:42.006 --> 00:20:44.616 A:middle
But one of the side effects is

00:20:44.616 --> 00:20:47.486 A:middle
that the controllers
class method is going

00:20:47.486 --> 00:20:51.086 A:middle
to be empty inside of
application did finish launching

00:20:51.086 --> 00:20:53.726 A:middle
for options with options.

00:20:55.216 --> 00:20:58.646 A:middle
But this is OK, if you setup
your notifications there

00:20:59.006 --> 00:21:01.666 A:middle
for controllers connecting
and disconnecting inside

WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:21:01.666 --> 00:21:03.066 A:middle
of application did
finish launching

00:21:03.066 --> 00:21:05.186 A:middle
with options you're
guaranteed not

00:21:05.186 --> 00:21:07.026 A:middle
to miss any connections
and disconnections.

00:21:07.586 --> 00:21:10.956 A:middle
Now, we recognize there
are some games out there

00:21:11.836 --> 00:21:15.546 A:middle
who might have large engines
or a lot of art assets to load.

00:21:15.546 --> 00:21:18.686 A:middle
And their not ready
to start listening

00:21:18.686 --> 00:21:21.106 A:middle
for controller notifications
inside

00:21:21.106 --> 00:21:23.176 A:middle
of application did finish
launching with options.

00:21:23.656 --> 00:21:24.566 A:middle
And that's OK.

00:21:25.136 --> 00:21:28.126 A:middle
You can call-- you can setup
your notifications whenever make

00:21:28.126 --> 00:21:29.156 A:middle
sense for your game.

00:21:29.606 --> 00:21:33.036 A:middle
Just make sure right before that
you call the controllers array

00:21:33.336 --> 00:21:34.766 A:middle
so you capture any controllers

00:21:34.766 --> 00:21:36.846 A:middle
which may have already
been connected.

00:21:41.176 --> 00:21:43.866 A:middle
All right, so now we have
controllers that are connected

00:21:43.956 --> 00:21:46.486 A:middle
and we're ready to read the
input off of those controllers.

00:21:47.886 --> 00:21:50.296 A:middle
Now, you recall we have
three supported physical

00:21:50.296 --> 00:21:51.276 A:middle
controller types.

00:21:51.836 --> 00:21:53.816 A:middle
And the way these are mapped

00:21:53.816 --> 00:21:57.066 A:middle
in the software are via
what we call profiles.

00:21:57.876 --> 00:22:02.136 A:middle
So, the standard gamepad has
a standard gamepad profile.

WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:22:03.156 --> 00:22:09.626 A:middle
And the two extended gamepads
share a single profile

00:22:09.626 --> 00:22:12.036 A:middle
that we call he extended
gamepad profile.

00:22:13.296 --> 00:22:16.796 A:middle
Now, the standard gamepad
profile that's why the standard

00:22:16.796 --> 00:22:18.946 A:middle
gamepad has four face buttons,

00:22:19.306 --> 00:22:21.466 A:middle
two shoulder buttons
and a D-pad.

00:22:21.466 --> 00:22:23.286 A:middle
And the way these are mapped

00:22:23.286 --> 00:22:26.086 A:middle
in the software are via
properties on the gamepad.

00:22:26.816 --> 00:22:30.326 A:middle
So, you have button A,
button B, button X, button Y.

00:22:31.086 --> 00:22:34.406 A:middle
Left shoulder, right
shoulder and D-pad.

00:22:36.456 --> 00:22:39.396 A:middle
Now, the standard gamepad
profile is a property called

00:22:39.496 --> 00:22:41.776 A:middle
gamepad on controllers.

00:22:42.216 --> 00:22:43.866 A:middle
You can see that listed
up in the subheading.

00:22:43.866 --> 00:22:50.106 A:middle
Moving on to the extended
gamepads you will recall these

00:22:50.106 --> 00:22:53.466 A:middle
add two thumbsticks
and two triggers on top

00:22:53.466 --> 00:22:55.286 A:middle
of the standard gamepad.

00:22:55.896 --> 00:23:01.366 A:middle
And here highlighted in yellow
you can see the extra properties

WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:23:01.366 --> 00:23:03.156 A:middle
on the extended gamepad profile.

00:23:03.766 --> 00:23:08.906 A:middle
Now, the standard gamepad
is going to be supported

00:23:08.906 --> 00:23:11.036 A:middle
by all controllers regardless

00:23:11.336 --> 00:23:13.026 A:middle
of whether it's a
standard controller

00:23:13.296 --> 00:23:14.446 A:middle
or an extended controller.

00:23:14.806 --> 00:23:18.756 A:middle
So, you as software developers
are guaranteed that as long

00:23:18.756 --> 00:23:20.636 A:middle
as your controller supports,

00:23:20.696 --> 00:23:24.086 A:middle
as long as your code supports
the standard gamepad all the

00:23:24.086 --> 00:23:27.586 A:middle
controllers that are used
with games will work.

00:23:28.726 --> 00:23:32.296 A:middle
With extended gamepads not every
controller will support the

00:23:32.296 --> 00:23:36.576 A:middle
extended gamepad profile namely
the standard gamepad obliviously

00:23:36.576 --> 00:23:37.656 A:middle
doesn't have thumbsticks.

00:23:37.656 --> 00:23:38.786 A:middle
It doesn't have triggers.

00:23:39.296 --> 00:23:40.556 A:middle
So, check this property,

00:23:40.556 --> 00:23:43.456 A:middle
check the extended gamepad
property on controllers.

00:23:43.706 --> 00:23:45.096 A:middle
If it's new hat means

00:23:45.096 --> 00:23:46.926 A:middle
that extended gamepads
are not supported.

00:23:47.026 --> 00:23:52.056 A:middle
I'd like to bring your attention
to the fact that thumbsticks

00:23:52.156 --> 00:23:55.306 A:middle
and D-pads while being two
totally physically separate

00:23:55.306 --> 00:23:58.816 A:middle
devices share a control
type direction pad.

WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:24:00.116 --> 00:24:03.276 A:middle
Similarly, the triggers
and the face buttons

00:24:03.756 --> 00:24:06.266 A:middle
and the shoulder buttons all
share a button input type.

00:24:07.126 --> 00:24:10.006 A:middle
So, let's dive into these
various element types.

00:24:12.116 --> 00:24:14.346 A:middle
Buttons are represented
in our framework

00:24:14.546 --> 00:24:16.956 A:middle
by a class called
GCControllerButtonInput.

00:24:17.456 --> 00:24:18.806 A:middle
And they are treated

00:24:18.806 --> 00:24:21.666 A:middle
in the classic digital sense
whether they're pressed or not

00:24:22.086 --> 00:24:24.316 A:middle
with a bullion in the
framework called Pressed.

00:24:25.436 --> 00:24:28.276 A:middle
If this is true the button is
pressed, if not its not pressed.

00:24:29.236 --> 00:24:32.346 A:middle
But since our buttons are also
pressure sensitive you have the

00:24:32.346 --> 00:24:36.666 A:middle
option of reading a value
property which returns a float.

00:24:36.916 --> 00:24:39.676 A:middle
This tells you how much force
that button is being pressed

00:24:39.676 --> 00:24:40.836 A:middle
with at the current moment.

00:24:41.716 --> 00:24:44.416 A:middle
And this is a float
normalized between zero and one.

00:24:44.416 --> 00:24:49.646 A:middle
All right, let's talk about
GCControllerDirectionPad.

00:24:50.036 --> 00:24:53.246 A:middle
Again, this is shared across
multiple physical inputs

00:24:53.426 --> 00:24:55.936 A:middle
such as the D-pad
and the thumbstick.

00:24:56.066 --> 00:25:00.116 A:middle
And we give you options as
game developers to use these

WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:25:00.116 --> 00:25:01.516 A:middle
in a way that suits your game.

00:25:02.236 --> 00:25:05.896 A:middle
So, you can read them as four
buttons up, down, left and right

00:25:06.956 --> 00:25:09.906 A:middle
or you can read them as two
axis, the xAxis and the yAxis.

00:25:09.966 --> 00:25:17.806 A:middle
If we look at the axis type
GCControllerAxisInput you will

00:25:17.806 --> 00:25:19.666 A:middle
note that it has
a value property.

00:25:20.356 --> 00:25:23.076 A:middle
And this tracks the
movement along that axis.

00:25:23.436 --> 00:25:27.136 A:middle
It's normalized from negative
one on one end to positive one

00:25:27.136 --> 00:25:29.866 A:middle
on the other end
with zero in between.

00:25:30.786 --> 00:25:32.526 A:middle
Now, the hardware
spec guarantees

00:25:32.526 --> 00:25:36.916 A:middle
that any non-zero value is the
player intentionally moving the

00:25:36.916 --> 00:25:38.706 A:middle
D-pad or the thumbstick away

00:25:38.706 --> 00:25:40.046 A:middle
from the neutral
resting position.

00:25:40.756 --> 00:25:42.886 A:middle
So, for those of you in
the audience who are used

00:25:42.886 --> 00:25:44.426 A:middle
to programming your
own dead zones

00:25:44.426 --> 00:25:46.636 A:middle
for controllers don't
do that here.

00:25:46.996 --> 00:25:49.786 A:middle
The hardware spec guarantees
a consistent dead zone

00:25:50.196 --> 00:25:51.526 A:middle
and if you add your
own dead zone

00:25:51.526 --> 00:25:54.696 A:middle
on top you're compromising the
crispiness of the controls.

00:25:55.186 --> 00:25:59.736 A:middle
All right.

00:25:59.736 --> 00:26:02.876 A:middle
Now, let's talk about how do
we actually read the values off

WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:26:02.876 --> 00:26:04.226 A:middle
of these controller inputs.

00:26:04.556 --> 00:26:06.986 A:middle
The first and probably most
common way that you're going

00:26:06.986 --> 00:26:08.466 A:middle
to be doing this is via Polling.

00:26:09.196 --> 00:26:11.856 A:middle
Polling allows you to find
out what the current value

00:26:11.856 --> 00:26:14.136 A:middle
of that controller
input is right now.

00:26:14.576 --> 00:26:18.526 A:middle
Using conjunction with polling
every game loop you can track

00:26:18.806 --> 00:26:21.136 A:middle
the movement of various
controller inputs

00:26:21.136 --> 00:26:23.116 A:middle
across various frames
of your game,

00:26:23.416 --> 00:26:24.726 A:middle
things like thumbstick position.

00:26:25.156 --> 00:26:28.226 A:middle
Now, sometimes you don't want

00:26:28.226 --> 00:26:30.266 A:middle
to know what the current
value is right now.

00:26:30.546 --> 00:26:32.656 A:middle
You want to be notified
when the value changes.

00:26:33.786 --> 00:26:38.396 A:middle
And to be notified of this you
can use value change call backs.

00:26:39.876 --> 00:26:42.346 A:middle
So, you can use this in
scenarios where you want

00:26:42.346 --> 00:26:45.196 A:middle
to be notified when the player
starts polling the right trigger

00:26:45.196 --> 00:26:45.816 A:middle
for instance.

00:26:46.076 --> 00:26:47.616 A:middle
Setup a value change call back

00:26:47.616 --> 00:26:51.146 A:middle
and you'll be notified
when that happens.

00:26:51.356 --> 00:26:54.736 A:middle
Lastly you can take snapshots
and snapshots are ways

00:26:54.736 --> 00:26:58.206 A:middle
of capturing the entire
controller state in one object.

00:26:59.736 --> 00:27:01.996 A:middle
You can use this for
a lot of useful things

WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:27:01.996 --> 00:27:04.166 A:middle
like recording button input.

00:27:04.316 --> 00:27:08.056 A:middle
You can compare current
controller state this frame

00:27:08.056 --> 00:27:09.406 A:middle
to a previous frame.

00:27:09.836 --> 00:27:11.216 A:middle
You can record input to send

00:27:11.216 --> 00:27:14.536 A:middle
across the wire to--
to record to a file.

00:27:14.536 --> 00:27:18.556 A:middle
Now, let's look at
some examples.

00:27:19.236 --> 00:27:21.296 A:middle
For polling like I said
you're typically going

00:27:21.296 --> 00:27:23.236 A:middle
to be doing this each
game loop iteration

00:27:23.996 --> 00:27:25.266 A:middle
and it's really just a simple

00:27:25.266 --> 00:27:27.766 A:middle
as reading the properties
off of the profiles.

00:27:28.236 --> 00:27:31.806 A:middle
So, in this first example
we have the standard gamepad

00:27:31.866 --> 00:27:33.126 A:middle
profile on the controller

00:27:33.736 --> 00:27:36.386 A:middle
and from there we're showing
you two different ways

00:27:36.386 --> 00:27:38.126 A:middle
to read the states
of the Y button.

00:27:38.126 --> 00:27:42.516 A:middle
Next, we show an example

00:27:42.516 --> 00:27:45.996 A:middle
from the extended gamepad
profile three different ways

00:27:45.996 --> 00:27:48.596 A:middle
on how to read the Y
axis thumbstick value.

00:27:49.256 --> 00:27:50.726 A:middle
You can treat it as a Y axis

00:27:50.966 --> 00:27:56.526 A:middle
or you can read it
as the up button.

00:27:56.666 --> 00:27:59.966 A:middle
Now, here's a polling example
in context of game code.

WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:28:00.726 --> 00:28:01.896 A:middle
We've got our update method.

00:28:02.156 --> 00:28:03.926 A:middle
This is what's called
one each game loop.

00:28:04.856 --> 00:28:07.236 A:middle
And within there we grab the
profile off the controller,

00:28:07.236 --> 00:28:08.906 A:middle
the extended gamepad
in this case.

00:28:10.266 --> 00:28:13.406 A:middle
And all the while the right
trigger is being pressed we're

00:28:13.406 --> 00:28:14.576 A:middle
going to firing lasers.

00:28:15.626 --> 00:28:18.306 A:middle
While the left trigger is
being pressed we're going

00:28:18.306 --> 00:28:19.206 A:middle
to launch missiles.

00:28:19.746 --> 00:28:24.336 A:middle
And lastly, we're going to apply
thrust to our spaceship based

00:28:24.336 --> 00:28:28.006 A:middle
on the current value of the
thumbsticks Y axis value.

00:28:33.356 --> 00:28:36.916 A:middle
Now, value change
handlers are accomplished

00:28:36.916 --> 00:28:38.096 A:middle
by passing in a block.

00:28:38.096 --> 00:28:40.696 A:middle
So, you choose which
controller element you want

00:28:40.696 --> 00:28:42.416 A:middle
to be notified when it changes.

00:28:42.606 --> 00:28:46.046 A:middle
And you also pass a block
of code that runs whenever

00:28:46.046 --> 00:28:47.926 A:middle
that value does happen
to change.

00:28:48.486 --> 00:28:51.116 A:middle
The framework is constantly
updating the profiles

00:28:51.116 --> 00:28:53.226 A:middle
on the main thread
at sixty hertz.

00:28:53.226 --> 00:28:57.586 A:middle
And we'll notify any value
change handlers you have setup.

00:28:58.186 --> 00:29:01.256 A:middle
Now, handlers can be
registered on specific elements

WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:29:01.466 --> 00:29:02.896 A:middle
such as individual buttons.

00:29:03.886 --> 00:29:06.136 A:middle
They can be registered on
collections of elements

00:29:06.316 --> 00:29:10.506 A:middle
such as the D-pad or thumbsticks
or they can be registered

00:29:10.506 --> 00:29:12.766 A:middle
on the entire controller
profile itself.

00:29:12.766 --> 00:29:14.486 A:middle
So, you can be notified
when anything

00:29:14.486 --> 00:29:15.486 A:middle
on the controller changes.

00:29:16.796 --> 00:29:17.576 A:middle
Here's an example.

00:29:17.576 --> 00:29:20.946 A:middle
So, again we grab the
profile off of the controller.

00:29:21.666 --> 00:29:24.216 A:middle
And this is an alternate way

00:29:24.216 --> 00:29:26.786 A:middle
of firing our lasers whenever
the right trigger is pressed.

00:29:27.176 --> 00:29:28.076 A:middle
So, we get a value--

00:29:28.076 --> 00:29:32.106 A:middle
value change handler which calls
us whenever the right trigger's

00:29:32.106 --> 00:29:33.046 A:middle
position changes.

00:29:33.476 --> 00:29:36.556 A:middle
When it does we check if
the button is pressed and if

00:29:36.596 --> 00:29:37.896 A:middle
so we fire our lasers.

00:29:37.896 --> 00:29:41.646 A:middle
Let's look at another example.

00:29:41.966 --> 00:29:48.016 A:middle
You can share a single handler
among several-- several inputs.

00:29:48.516 --> 00:29:50.806 A:middle
So, in this case we're
implementing a touch any button

00:29:50.806 --> 00:29:51.386 A:middle
to continue.

00:29:52.146 --> 00:29:53.636 A:middle
We grab the profile.

00:29:53.636 --> 00:29:57.536 A:middle
We setup our handler which we're
calling myFaceButtonsHandler.

00:29:58.266 --> 00:30:00.896 A:middle
And then we assign
that handler to each

WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:30:00.896 --> 00:30:01.976 A:middle
of the four face buttons.

00:30:03.166 --> 00:30:06.506 A:middle
When any of them are
pressed the code runs

00:30:06.506 --> 00:30:10.696 A:middle
and we dismiss the
UI in this case.

00:30:10.886 --> 00:30:13.706 A:middle
Lastly, an example on how to
setup value change handlers

00:30:13.706 --> 00:30:14.956 A:middle
on collections of elements.

00:30:15.576 --> 00:30:21.016 A:middle
In this case whenever the
right thumbstick is moved we

00:30:21.016 --> 00:30:22.156 A:middle
get notified.

00:30:22.156 --> 00:30:24.076 A:middle
This is good for situation
where you might want

00:30:24.076 --> 00:30:26.526 A:middle
to say move the right
thumbstick to look around

00:30:26.866 --> 00:30:31.656 A:middle
and be notified when
that happens.

00:30:31.656 --> 00:30:35.226 A:middle
Now, value change handlers are
called in a hierarchical order

00:30:35.886 --> 00:30:39.466 A:middle
from individual elements
through the collections and on,

00:30:39.466 --> 00:30:41.126 A:middle
up into the controller itself.

00:30:42.106 --> 00:30:44.656 A:middle
So, example of a
D-pad being pressed.

00:30:46.116 --> 00:30:47.606 A:middle
First the framework checks

00:30:47.606 --> 00:30:49.486 A:middle
if there are any
value change handlers

00:30:49.646 --> 00:30:51.566 A:middle
on the four face buttons--

00:30:51.566 --> 00:30:53.716 A:middle
or sorry, the four buttons
that represent the D-pad.

00:30:54.336 --> 00:30:55.866 A:middle
If so those are called.

00:30:56.676 --> 00:30:59.386 A:middle
Then it goes through the
two axis on the D-pad.

00:30:59.746 --> 00:31:01.496 A:middle
If you have setup
value change handlers

WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:31:01.496 --> 00:31:03.446 A:middle
for those they are
called as well.

00:31:04.146 --> 00:31:07.076 A:middle
Then it calls the value change
handler on the D-pad itself

00:31:07.196 --> 00:31:09.336 A:middle
if you've assigned
one and lastly

00:31:09.336 --> 00:31:10.616 A:middle
on to the controller profile.

00:31:14.846 --> 00:31:15.416 A:middle
All right.

00:31:15.416 --> 00:31:16.846 A:middle
Let's talk about snapshots now.

00:31:17.236 --> 00:31:21.266 A:middle
Snapshots allow us to collect
the entire current controller's

00:31:21.266 --> 00:31:22.906 A:middle
state in one object.

00:31:23.486 --> 00:31:27.536 A:middle
And we allow you to
move the data from to

00:31:27.536 --> 00:31:30.536 A:middle
and from NSData Objects
very easily via methods

00:31:30.536 --> 00:31:31.716 A:middle
that I'll show you in a moment.

00:31:32.476 --> 00:31:34.476 A:middle
And once you have an
NSData Representation

00:31:34.476 --> 00:31:36.876 A:middle
of the snapshot you can do
whatever you want with it.

00:31:36.876 --> 00:31:37.946 A:middle
You can start to file.

00:31:37.946 --> 00:31:39.186 A:middle
You can start to URL.

00:31:39.526 --> 00:31:41.036 A:middle
You can unpack it after that.

00:31:42.196 --> 00:31:44.616 A:middle
Snapshots are also
mutable so in addition

00:31:44.616 --> 00:31:49.096 A:middle
to recording a controller input
you can retrieve controller

00:31:49.096 --> 00:31:51.516 A:middle
input and assign it
back into a snapshot.

00:31:52.056 --> 00:31:55.516 A:middle
Now, you're going to want to
use snapshots in conjunction

00:31:55.516 --> 00:31:57.886 A:middle
with polling or value
change handlers.

00:31:58.326 --> 00:31:59.546 A:middle
So, in your main game loop

00:31:59.546 --> 00:32:02.336 A:middle
as your polling you could be
collecting snapshots each frame

WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:32:03.046 --> 00:32:05.906 A:middle
or inside your value change
handlers you could be collecting

00:32:05.906 --> 00:32:06.906 A:middle
snapshots as well.

00:32:07.846 --> 00:32:11.486 A:middle
This is great for recording
controller input, for sending it

00:32:11.486 --> 00:32:14.206 A:middle
over a network, for various
debugging activities.

00:32:14.586 --> 00:32:17.486 A:middle
Let's look at us a controller--
or sorry, a snapshot example.

00:32:18.226 --> 00:32:20.426 A:middle
So, in this example we're
going to take a snapshot

00:32:20.426 --> 00:32:21.866 A:middle
and write it to a file.

00:32:22.896 --> 00:32:25.816 A:middle
To do that we call the
save snapshot method

00:32:26.246 --> 00:32:27.656 A:middle
on the gamepad profile.

00:32:28.546 --> 00:32:31.716 A:middle
This gives us our snapshot
object GCGamepadSnapshot.

00:32:33.006 --> 00:32:36.706 A:middle
Then we use a method on
GCGamepadSnapshot called--

00:32:36.966 --> 00:32:38.846 A:middle
or a property called
snapshotData

00:32:38.846 --> 00:32:43.436 A:middle
and that gives us the NSData
representation of the snapshot

00:32:43.436 --> 00:32:46.726 A:middle
and then using NSData we
can go ahead and write

00:32:46.726 --> 00:32:48.296 A:middle
that snapshot to a file.

00:32:49.456 --> 00:32:51.156 A:middle
Let's look at an example
going to the other way.

00:32:51.836 --> 00:32:54.656 A:middle
So, in this case we provide
a file and we use NSData

00:32:54.656 --> 00:32:56.416 A:middle
to retrieve that file.

00:32:56.986 --> 00:33:01.306 A:middle
And then we go ahead and
initialize a snapshot object

WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:33:01.426 --> 00:33:04.686 A:middle
with that using our
initWithSnapshotData method.

00:33:07.716 --> 00:33:10.336 A:middle
And now I think its
time for a demo.

00:33:10.416 --> 00:33:14.346 A:middle
So, I'd to call Jacques back up
on stage and Tomash from Crytek.

00:33:15.176 --> 00:33:18.436 A:middle
